  "text": "METHODS -All the patients attending the diabetic foot clinic of the University of Pisa between April and October 2005 were screened for the following inclusion criteria: They should have type 1 or type 2 diabetes for a period of at least 5 years, they should have peripheral neuropathy as highlighted by insensitivity to a 10-g monofilament and by a vibration perception threshold measured at malleolus of at least 25 volts (15), and they should have a forefoot plantar ulcer for a period of at least 3 weeks with an area wider than 1 cm 2 graded 1A or 2A according to Texas University classification [CITATION_1] . The exclusion criteria considered were peripheral vascular disease with an anklebrachial pressure index Ͻ0.9; the presence of clinical signs of infection, including edema, erithema, increased local skin temperature, secretion, fever, and leukocytosis, confirmed by culture exams; previous ulcer in the same site in the last 6 months; probing to bone and/or radiographic signs of osteomyelitis; Charcot's neuroarthropathy of the foot; bilateral ulceration; serum creatinine Ͼ2 mg/dl; any systemic pathology or therapy possibly interfering with the healing process; severe visual or motor impairment that could expose the patient to risk of accidents while participating in the study; and/or a life expectancy shorter than 1 year.",
